⁸ Lioeae.] The Lixae were a set of fellows who attended the camp for service, and were mostly washers⁷ bakers, and cooks for dressing victuals ς or buffoons and players for the entertainment and diversion of the officers and persons of note in the army. But the having a great many of these Lixae in the camp was inconsistent with the an- cient strict discipline of the Romans, which obliged the common sol- diets to grind their own corn7 bake their own bread, dress their own victuals, and be servants in every particular to themselves—M.
